One of the most consequential developments behind the declining competitiveness of American PV took place outside the PV industry. In the 1970s, Japanese firms made inroads into industries related to PV, conquering almost half of the global semiconductor market and wiping out large parts of the American consumer electronics industry (
 
  108
 ). These firms viewed PV as a complementary investment to their existing capabilities, where they could plow some of their retained earnings (
 
